<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-03-27T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-03-27T14:00:00-05:00" n="239" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d239">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72119/3943a: Telegram</note>
                    <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                            to the Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Wallace</hi></persName>)</head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-03-27T14:00:00-05:00">March 27, 1919—2
                            p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                    <p>7853. Department’s 7549, February 27th. Your attention is called to the fact
                        that no reports whatever on the general attitude of the French press have
                        been received for the past ten days. Department requests that it be kept
                        more fully advised on this subject.</p>
                    <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi></signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>